1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:05,930

2
00:00:05,930 --> 00:00:07,290
Welcome, everyone.

3
00:00:07,290 --> 00:00:09,050
I want to thank you
for joining us today

4
00:00:09,050 --> 00:00:10,820
for what will be a
terrific conversation

5
00:00:10,820 --> 00:00:13,890
with our esteemed guest,
Professor Esther Duflo,

6
00:00:13,890 --> 00:00:16,860
here at the Massachusetts
Institute of Technology.

7
00:00:16,860 --> 00:00:19,880
We'll hear from Dr. Duflo about
her groundbreaking research

8
00:00:19,880 --> 00:00:22,320
and approaches to
poverty alleviation.

9
00:00:22,320 --> 00:00:25,760
And we'll also talk in
depth about her teaching

10
00:00:25,760 --> 00:00:28,980
and how sharing teaching openly
through MIT Open Learning,

11
00:00:28,980 --> 00:00:31,820
and more broadly, has had
a transformative impact

12
00:00:31,820 --> 00:00:35,540
on the lives of people at
MIT and around the world.

13
00:00:35,540 --> 00:00:36,690
I'm Chris Capozzola.

14
00:00:36,690 --> 00:00:39,770
I'm our Senior Associate Dean
for Open Learning here at MIT.

15
00:00:39,770 --> 00:00:43,400
And this is the second event
in the Open Conversation series

16
00:00:43,400 --> 00:00:48,080
that Open Learning hosts, that
focuses on how Open Learning can

17
00:00:48,080 --> 00:00:50,940
empower people to improve
their lives, communities,

18
00:00:50,940 --> 00:00:52,310
and the world.

19
00:00:52,310 --> 00:00:55,850
And our special guest today
is Professor Esther Duflo.

20
00:00:55,850 --> 00:00:58,250
And I have the pleasure
of introducing her.

21
00:00:58,250 --> 00:01:01,270
And her accomplishments
are many,

22
00:01:01,270 --> 00:01:04,129
and her achievements
are phenomenal.

23
00:01:04,129 --> 00:01:06,190
I will just briefly
introduce you to her

24
00:01:06,190 --> 00:01:08,590
as a researcher and a scholar.

25
00:01:08,590 --> 00:01:11,710
Dr. Duflo is the Abdul
Latif Jameel Professor

26
00:01:11,710 --> 00:01:14,680
of Poverty Alleviation
and Development Economics

27
00:01:14,680 --> 00:01:16,690
here at MIT.

28
00:01:16,690 --> 00:01:20,050
She's the Co-Founder and
Co-Director of the Abdul Latif

29
00:01:20,050 --> 00:01:25,180
Jameel Poverty Action Lab, and
Chair of Pauvreté et Publique

30
00:01:25,180 --> 00:01:26,980
at the College de France.

31
00:01:26,980 --> 00:01:30,700
In her research, she seeks to
understand the economic lives

32
00:01:30,700 --> 00:01:35,590
of people who live in poverty,
with the aim of designing

33
00:01:35,590 --> 00:01:39,130
and evaluating rigorously
social policies for poverty

34
00:01:39,130 --> 00:01:40,160
alleviation.

35
00:01:40,160 --> 00:01:44,320
She's worked on health, on
education, financial inclusion,

36
00:01:44,320 --> 00:01:47,660
environments and
sustainability, and governance.

37
00:01:47,660 --> 00:01:51,250
And she has been the recipient
of numerous academic honors

38
00:01:51,250 --> 00:01:55,390
and prizes, many of which
are what probably encouraged

39
00:01:55,390 --> 00:01:58,600
you to log in here today,
including, of course,

40
00:01:58,600 --> 00:02:01,240
the 2019 Nobel
Prize in economics,

41
00:02:01,240 --> 00:02:04,020
which she shared with
co-laureates Abhijit Banerjee

42
00:02:04,020 --> 00:02:08,759
and Michael Kremer, a John Bates
Clark Medal, and the MacArthur

43
00:02:08,759 --> 00:02:13,260
so-called Genius Fellowship,
to name just a few among many.

44
00:02:13,260 --> 00:02:16,620
She's the author, most recently,
of the prize-winning book Poor

45
00:02:16,620 --> 00:02:20,190
Economics, A Radical
Rethinking of the Way to Fight

46
00:02:20,190 --> 00:02:22,980
Global Poverty, which I
encourage you to check out.

47
00:02:22,980 --> 00:02:25,750
And near and dear to
our heart here at MIT,

48
00:02:25,750 --> 00:02:28,270
she is a dedicated and
innovative teacher,

49
00:02:28,270 --> 00:02:31,590
not only here on our campus in
both graduate and undergraduate

50
00:02:31,590 --> 00:02:35,130
education, but in conjunction
with Open Learning,

51
00:02:35,130 --> 00:02:37,680
where she shares her teaching
with tens of thousands

52
00:02:37,680 --> 00:02:39,330
of learners worldwide.

53
00:02:39,330 --> 00:02:43,380
So what we'll be doing
for the next hour

54
00:02:43,380 --> 00:02:46,590
is talking back and
forth with Dr. Duflo.

55
00:02:46,590 --> 00:02:48,930
We're going to hear
some of her passions

56
00:02:48,930 --> 00:02:52,530
for teaching and learning, some
of her insights and thoughts

57
00:02:52,530 --> 00:02:55,580
right now about
poverty alleviation

58
00:02:55,580 --> 00:03:00,320
and challenges in economics
as practiced in the world.

59
00:03:00,320 --> 00:03:02,528
And we'll be bringing in
questions from our audience.

60
00:03:02,528 --> 00:03:04,278
Some of those are
questions that have come

61
00:03:04,278 --> 00:03:05,580
to the audience ahead of time.

62
00:03:05,580 --> 00:03:08,270
And some are ones that
you can continue to offer

63
00:03:08,270 --> 00:03:10,290
if you're watching this live.

64
00:03:10,290 --> 00:03:13,200
So I'm going to just start
off by giving you the floor.

65
00:03:13,200 --> 00:03:16,100
And I'd love to just hear
a little bit about you

66
00:03:16,100 --> 00:03:20,480
and what inspired you to
take this path for research

67
00:03:20,480 --> 00:03:23,720
and to focus on
economics, public policy,

68
00:03:23,720 --> 00:03:28,340
and really using data to
advance poverty alleviation.

69
00:03:28,340 --> 00:03:29,510
First of all, thank you.

70
00:03:29,510 --> 00:03:33,770
Thank you all for being
here online and in person.

71
00:03:33,770 --> 00:03:35,930
I know there are so
many things happening

72
00:03:35,930 --> 00:03:39,530
at the end of May on campus that
it's pretty phenomenal that you

73
00:03:39,530 --> 00:03:40,100
made it here.

74
00:03:40,100 --> 00:03:44,750

75
00:03:44,750 --> 00:03:46,820
Most people, I think,
find a field of study,

76
00:03:46,820 --> 00:03:49,010
and then they look for a topic.

77
00:03:49,010 --> 00:03:51,325
And I went the other way.

78
00:03:51,325 --> 00:03:56,340
I had a topic, and then I had
finally found the field of study

79
00:03:56,340 --> 00:03:58,240
that would fit to that topic.

80
00:03:58,240 --> 00:04:06,300
So from really an early age, I
was very exposed to the notion

81
00:04:06,300 --> 00:04:09,140
that there are poor people
around in the world--

82
00:04:09,140 --> 00:04:12,390
poor kids, when I was a kid, I
was more interested in kids--

83
00:04:12,390 --> 00:04:16,860
that had circumstances that
were widely different from mine.

84
00:04:16,860 --> 00:04:20,220
Part of it because my
mom was a pediatrician,

85
00:04:20,220 --> 00:04:23,260
and she had an
office in the city.

86
00:04:23,260 --> 00:04:26,670
But she also was very
involved in an NGO

87
00:04:26,670 --> 00:04:30,930
that was working with
children victims of war.

88
00:04:30,930 --> 00:04:33,900
In fact, the country where she
spent a lot of her time working

89
00:04:33,900 --> 00:04:38,960
is now very much in the news
because it's El Salvador.

90
00:04:38,960 --> 00:04:43,110
But before that, she went
to many other countries.

91
00:04:43,110 --> 00:04:48,150
And she would come back
and show us slideshows

92
00:04:48,150 --> 00:04:50,860
of what she had seen.

93
00:04:50,860 --> 00:04:57,470
And it kind of struck
me that these children,

94
00:04:57,470 --> 00:05:02,450
just because they were
born in the wrong country

95
00:05:02,450 --> 00:05:06,380
or in a different
set of circumstances,

96
00:05:06,380 --> 00:05:09,440
had a life that was so
much harder and probably

97
00:05:09,440 --> 00:05:12,180
so much more
circumscribed than mine,

98
00:05:12,180 --> 00:05:14,970
with so little opportunities.

99
00:05:14,970 --> 00:05:21,860
So I always thought,
this is a gigantic debt

100
00:05:21,860 --> 00:05:25,220
that I have to the world.

101
00:05:25,220 --> 00:05:29,020
Maybe it was somewhat
self-aggrandizing to think

102
00:05:29,020 --> 00:05:29,520
that way.

103
00:05:29,520 --> 00:05:32,180
But this is really how I thought
about it when I was little.

104
00:05:32,180 --> 00:05:36,980
And I have to devote
my life to repay

105
00:05:36,980 --> 00:05:41,270
that debt of the
incredible cosmic luck

106
00:05:41,270 --> 00:05:45,930
that I have to be born in
the middle class in Paris,

107
00:05:45,930 --> 00:05:50,902
as opposed to in the
Sahara or in the DRC

108
00:05:50,902 --> 00:05:51,860
or something like that.

109
00:05:51,860 --> 00:05:55,130
So it always stayed with me.

110
00:05:55,130 --> 00:05:59,170
And for the longest
time, I really

111
00:05:59,170 --> 00:06:02,930
didn't know how to put
that into practice.

112
00:06:02,930 --> 00:06:07,030
And I followed the path
of least resistance

113
00:06:07,030 --> 00:06:14,890
of a good student in France,
studying for exams and so on.

114
00:06:14,890 --> 00:06:18,640
As a matter of fact, I thought
I would be a historian.

115
00:06:18,640 --> 00:06:26,950
And came a time, somewhere
in the middle of college,

116
00:06:26,950 --> 00:06:31,670
where I felt that I was
really so protected,

117
00:06:31,670 --> 00:06:36,430
and I had a life that was so
comfortable, both intellectually

118
00:06:36,430 --> 00:06:38,845
and physically.

119
00:06:38,845 --> 00:06:42,320
I lived in this wonderful
dorm in the center of Paris.

120
00:06:42,320 --> 00:06:44,150
I was paid to study.

121
00:06:44,150 --> 00:06:46,070
I had the best friends.

122
00:06:46,070 --> 00:06:48,130
And we had classes,
like seminars,

123
00:06:48,130 --> 00:06:49,870
with five people
in them and so on.

124
00:06:49,870 --> 00:06:54,720
And it was like, I'm
making no progress

125
00:06:54,720 --> 00:06:56,410
in repaying my cosmic debt.

126
00:06:56,410 --> 00:06:59,280
And it made me a little jittery.

127
00:06:59,280 --> 00:07:02,260
So I decided I have
to change my path.

128
00:07:02,260 --> 00:07:06,540
And so I thought, maybe I
should go into politics,

129
00:07:06,540 --> 00:07:08,670
because I would have
a more direct impact

130
00:07:08,670 --> 00:07:10,210
on the life of people.

131
00:07:10,210 --> 00:07:15,600
But I was a little suspicious
that they would like it,

132
00:07:15,600 --> 00:07:18,840
because I don't
really like shortcuts.

133
00:07:18,840 --> 00:07:24,150
So I thought, OK, let me just
take a step back and move

134
00:07:24,150 --> 00:07:27,610
country and figure
out what I can do.

135
00:07:27,610 --> 00:07:31,740
And it turns out my school
had an exchange with Russia.

136
00:07:31,740 --> 00:07:34,410
So I was like, I'll go
to Russia for a year.

137
00:07:34,410 --> 00:07:36,280
And I went to Russia for a year.

138
00:07:36,280 --> 00:07:41,280
And I was teaching French
in a university there.

139
00:07:41,280 --> 00:07:45,820
And by some really totally
accidental reasons,

140
00:07:45,820 --> 00:07:46,775
I met two economists.

141
00:07:46,775 --> 00:07:48,650
One of them happened to
be a professor at MIT

142
00:07:48,650 --> 00:07:50,780
at the time, Thomas Piketty.

143
00:07:50,780 --> 00:07:53,550
And the other was a
professor back in my college.

144
00:07:53,550 --> 00:07:57,810
And through them, I got
in touch with many people,

145
00:07:57,810 --> 00:07:59,550
many economists in
Russia at that time.

146
00:07:59,550 --> 00:08:01,440
This was the middle
of the transition,

147
00:08:01,440 --> 00:08:03,590
so people were very busy.

148
00:08:03,590 --> 00:08:06,290
And I watched what
they were doing.

149
00:08:06,290 --> 00:08:09,720
They plugged me in to be a
research assistant and so on.

150
00:08:09,720 --> 00:08:11,600
I spoke Russian,
so I could be more

151
00:08:11,600 --> 00:08:15,990
or less useful despite
knowing no economics.

152
00:08:15,990 --> 00:08:22,070
And I watched with
a mixture of dread

153
00:08:22,070 --> 00:08:23,840
and being very
impressed what they

154
00:08:23,840 --> 00:08:27,350
were doing, because I thought
they have a tremendous amount

155
00:08:27,350 --> 00:08:28,320
of influence.

156
00:08:28,320 --> 00:08:29,880
And they were
academic economists,

157
00:08:29,880 --> 00:08:34,020
many of them from Harvard, who
were advising the government.

158
00:08:34,020 --> 00:08:38,059
And they were really
making major decisions

159
00:08:38,059 --> 00:08:44,000
or having their finger on
major decisions on the basis,

160
00:08:44,000 --> 00:08:46,083
I thought, of not
very much knowledge,

161
00:08:46,083 --> 00:08:48,250
because it's not that anybody
had a lot of knowledge

162
00:08:48,250 --> 00:08:52,180
about how to radically
turn the ship.

163
00:08:52,180 --> 00:08:54,890
But I thought, OK, this is it.

164
00:08:54,890 --> 00:08:57,050
I can go back to my cosmic debt.

165
00:08:57,050 --> 00:08:59,710
I'm going to learn
economics, and then I'm

166
00:08:59,710 --> 00:09:03,040
going to be able
to, as an academic,

167
00:09:03,040 --> 00:09:05,350
have influence,
maybe, on the way

168
00:09:05,350 --> 00:09:06,820
that economic
decisions are being

169
00:09:06,820 --> 00:09:08,630
made that concerns the poor.

170
00:09:08,630 --> 00:09:15,290
So with that plan hatched in
Russia, went back to France.

171
00:09:15,290 --> 00:09:19,180
I had to basically cram five
years of economics into one

172
00:09:19,180 --> 00:09:21,590
so that I could then
apply to graduate school.

173
00:09:21,590 --> 00:09:25,370
And then I came to MIT and
started working on this problem.

174
00:09:25,370 --> 00:09:26,330
So I came here.

175
00:09:26,330 --> 00:09:29,420
I think it was incredibly
lucky in a way,

176
00:09:29,420 --> 00:09:31,430
because I think for
many PhD students,

177
00:09:31,430 --> 00:09:33,600
after they are done
with their classes,

178
00:09:33,600 --> 00:09:36,520
they are a bit fumbling
around, figuring out what

179
00:09:36,520 --> 00:09:38,360
they should do research on.

180
00:09:38,360 --> 00:09:40,730
And I was on a mission.

181
00:09:40,730 --> 00:09:42,020
I still am on the mission.

182
00:09:42,020 --> 00:09:43,782
That's the same one.

183
00:09:43,782 --> 00:09:45,812
That's fantastic.

184
00:09:45,812 --> 00:09:48,180
It's great to hear that
story, and I think also

185
00:09:48,180 --> 00:09:52,890
for many people who start their
learning journey not knowing

186
00:09:52,890 --> 00:09:57,660
what intellectual tools will
solve the problems that they

187
00:09:57,660 --> 00:09:58,180
want to do.

188
00:09:58,180 --> 00:10:00,900
And that's a great story.

189
00:10:00,900 --> 00:10:04,720
Let me talk about you
becoming a teacher.

190
00:10:04,720 --> 00:10:10,770
So what inspires you
in the classroom?

191
00:10:10,770 --> 00:10:12,940
What do you get
most excited about,

192
00:10:12,940 --> 00:10:16,090
whether it's an in-person
classroom on campus

193
00:10:16,090 --> 00:10:18,780
or when you're teaching online?

194
00:10:18,780 --> 00:10:20,520
So in the story
that I tell, there

195
00:10:20,520 --> 00:10:23,700
are really these powerful
professor figures.

196
00:10:23,700 --> 00:10:26,530
My professor from France,
his name was Daniel Cohen.

197
00:10:26,530 --> 00:10:27,640
He recently passed away.

198
00:10:27,640 --> 00:10:32,640
He was an amazing
teacher in the sense

199
00:10:32,640 --> 00:10:40,080
that he was able to connect
quite complicated concepts

200
00:10:40,080 --> 00:10:49,460
to real-world situations and
make them speak to each other

201
00:10:49,460 --> 00:10:52,170
in ways that were
really remarkable.

202
00:10:52,170 --> 00:10:55,700
And he was also a great
exponent of writing

203
00:10:55,700 --> 00:10:58,615
excellent popular audience
books for the same reason.

204
00:10:58,615 --> 00:11:02,180

205
00:11:02,180 --> 00:11:06,020
And that was, of course,
very important in my decision

206
00:11:06,020 --> 00:11:10,910
to switch to economics, because
in the course of working

207
00:11:10,910 --> 00:11:12,920
for him, I had
really the occasion

208
00:11:12,920 --> 00:11:15,912
of hearing the way
he was talking.

209
00:11:15,912 --> 00:11:19,110
And of course, at various
other moments in my life,

210
00:11:19,110 --> 00:11:21,150
I was exposed to
wonderful teachers.

211
00:11:21,150 --> 00:11:27,800
So it's pretty essential
to I think the--

212
00:11:27,800 --> 00:11:30,600
people meet many,
many people, I'm sure,

213
00:11:30,600 --> 00:11:36,200
who are able to pinpoint the
one teacher in their life

214
00:11:36,200 --> 00:11:39,990
or the several teachers in their
life, either in grade school

215
00:11:39,990 --> 00:11:44,050
or in high school or in
college, that made a difference.

216
00:11:44,050 --> 00:11:46,710

217
00:11:46,710 --> 00:11:48,750
Teaching at MIT
and teaching online

218
00:11:48,750 --> 00:11:53,230
is, of course, a very
different ball game.

219
00:11:53,230 --> 00:11:55,560
It's a different objectives.

220
00:11:55,560 --> 00:11:59,050
The MIT students
are amazingly sharp.

221
00:11:59,050 --> 00:12:01,420
And especially, I
teach a freshman class,

222
00:12:01,420 --> 00:12:07,230
which I really love to teach
because I assume that nothing is

223
00:12:07,230 --> 00:12:09,960
known and that
it's a blank page,

224
00:12:09,960 --> 00:12:17,460
but that there is no concept
that you cannot bring.

225
00:12:17,460 --> 00:12:21,450
And I think this attitude, I
try to take to all my teaching

226
00:12:21,450 --> 00:12:24,630
and my writing, whether
it's at MIT or online,

227
00:12:24,630 --> 00:12:29,250
is to never, never, never assume
that the person in front of you

228
00:12:29,250 --> 00:12:31,800
is not ultra sharp
and ultra smart

229
00:12:31,800 --> 00:12:34,560
and can't understand
what you're telling them.

230
00:12:34,560 --> 00:12:37,150
So anything can be approached.

231
00:12:37,150 --> 00:12:38,900
And in fact, in
France, you mentioned

232
00:12:38,900 --> 00:12:42,290
my teaching gig in France is
kind of an on and on teaching

233
00:12:42,290 --> 00:12:42,840
gig.

234
00:12:42,840 --> 00:12:44,460
It's totally open.

235
00:12:44,460 --> 00:12:46,800
There are 2,000 people
in the auditorium.

236
00:12:46,800 --> 00:12:49,730
Most of them are above 70,
and they have never done

237
00:12:49,730 --> 00:12:51,210
economics in their whole life.

238
00:12:51,210 --> 00:12:53,790
And I teach them the same
thing that I teach at MIT.

239
00:12:53,790 --> 00:12:54,290
Nice.

240
00:12:54,290 --> 00:12:55,620
But not in the same way.

241
00:12:55,620 --> 00:12:57,890
Nice.

242
00:12:57,890 --> 00:13:01,010
So it's really lovely to teach
to MIT students, undergraduates

243
00:13:01,010 --> 00:13:02,340
or graduate students.

244
00:13:02,340 --> 00:13:04,910
The undergraduates, what I
like or love with the freshmen

245
00:13:04,910 --> 00:13:07,230
also is I teach a
communication intensive class,

246
00:13:07,230 --> 00:13:12,980
so I make people talk and
prepare things and get engaged

247
00:13:12,980 --> 00:13:16,230
with really practical problems.

248
00:13:16,230 --> 00:13:20,700
And they are delighted to
have a chance to speak up.

249
00:13:20,700 --> 00:13:23,220
So it's very nice to
